1
00:01:35,492 --> 00:01:37,980
Yeah, I worked
in a barber shop,

2
00:01:38,083 --> 00:01:40,985
But I never considered
myself a barber.

3
00:01:41,092 --> 00:01:45,347
I stumbled into it well,
married into it, more precisely.

4
00:01:45,444 --> 00:01:49,241
It wasn't my establishment.
Like the fella says, I only work here.

5
00:01:52,452 --> 00:01:54,077
The dump was 200 feet square...

6
00:01:54,340 --> 00:01:56,958
With three chairs,
or stations, as we call 'em,

7
00:01:57,220 --> 00:01:59,260
Even though there are only
two of us working.

8
00:01:59,363 --> 00:02:02,047
But this is my point.

9
00:02:02,147 --> 00:02:05,344
My point is that these traders and trappers
would come to this country,

10
00:02:05,444 --> 00:02:07,549
Get their pelts
and their gold "ignots"

11
00:02:07,812 --> 00:02:10,626
Frank Raffo, my brother-in-law,
was the principal barber.

12
00:02:10,692 --> 00:02:12,066
Man, could he talk.

13
00:02:13,892 --> 00:02:17,504
Maybe if you're 11 or 12 years old,
Frank's got an interesting point of view,

14
00:02:17,572 --> 00:02:19,939
But sometimes
it got on my nerves.

15
00:02:20,035 --> 00:02:21,726
Not that I complained,
mind you.

16
00:02:21,827 --> 00:02:24,161
Like I said, he was
the principal Barber.

17
00:02:25,156 --> 00:02:27,577
Frank's father August
they called him Guzzi

18
00:02:27,684 --> 00:02:30,237
Had worked the heads up
in Santa Rosa for 35 years...

19
00:02:30,339 --> 00:02:33,023
Until his ticker stopped
in the middle of a junior flattop.

20
00:02:33,092 --> 00:02:36,256
He left the shop to Frankie free and clear,

21
00:02:36,355 --> 00:02:38,843
And that seemed to satisfy
all of Frank's ambitions

22
00:02:38,948 --> 00:02:41,631
Cutting the hair
and chewing the fat.

23
00:02:41,732 --> 00:02:44,383
Me, I don't talk much.

24
00:02:49,156 --> 00:02:50,944
I just cut the hair.

25
00:02:58,883 --> 00:03:01,731
It says here that the russians
exploded an a-bomb...

26
00:03:01,828 --> 00:03:04,610
And there's not a damn thing
we can do about it.

27
00:03:07,075 --> 00:03:08,985
How do you like them apples?

28
00:03:14,564 --> 00:03:17,630
Being a barber is a lot like
being a bar man or a soda jerk.

29
00:03:17,891 --> 00:03:21,917
There's not much to it once
you've learned the basic moves.

30
00:03:22,019 --> 00:03:23,907
For the kids, there's the butch,
or the heinie,

31
00:03:23,972 --> 00:03:25,859
The flattop, the ivy,

32
00:03:25,955 --> 00:03:27,646
The crew, the vanguard,

33
00:03:27,748 --> 00:03:29,089
The junior contour...

34
00:03:29,187 --> 00:03:32,503
And occasionally
the executive contour.

35
00:03:33,891 --> 00:03:37,503
lived in a little bungalow
on napa street.

36
00:03:37,571 --> 00:03:39,294
The place was okay, I guess.

37
00:03:39,395 --> 00:03:42,395
Had an electric icebox,
a gas hearth...

38
00:03:42,499 --> 00:03:45,347
And a garbage grinde
built into the sink.

39
00:03:45,444 --> 00:03:47,713
You might say I had it made.

40
00:03:47,812 --> 00:03:50,267
Oh, year,
there was one other thing.

41
00:03:52,035 --> 00:03:54,337
Doris kept the books
at Nirdlingers,

42
00:03:54,403 --> 00:03:56,705
A small department store
on main street.

43
00:03:56,771 --> 00:03:59,138
Doris liked the work,
accounting.

44
00:03:59,203 --> 00:04:01,691
She liked knowing
where everything stood

45
00:04:01,795 --> 00:04:05,472
And she got a ten percent employee
discount on whatever she wanted

46
00:04:05,571 --> 00:04:07,033
Nylon stockings,

47
00:04:07,139 --> 00:04:09,823
Makeup and perfume.

48
00:04:11,651 --> 00:04:14,204
Doris and I went to church
once a week.

49
00:04:15,171 --> 00:04:17,538
Usually Tuesday night.

50
00:04:24,387 --> 00:04:27,137
Doris wasn't big
on divine worship,

51
00:04:27,235 --> 00:04:30,333
And I doubt if she believed
in life everlasting.

52
00:04:30,404 --> 00:04:33,251
She'd most likely tell you
that our reward is on this earth,

53
00:04:33,347 --> 00:04:35,932
And bingo is probably
the extent of it.

54
00:04:36,035 --> 00:04:37,562
B-7

55
00:04:37,667 --> 00:04:38,812
Watch you card,
honey.

56
00:04:38,915 --> 00:04:41,697
I wasn't crazy
about the game,

57
00:04:41,763 --> 00:04:43,771
But, I don't know,
it made her happy,

58
00:04:43,875 --> 00:04:46,842
And I found the setting
peaceful.

59
00:04:46,947 --> 00:04:48,289
Jesus. Bingo.

60
00:04:48,387 --> 00:04:49,533
Bingo!

61
00:04:50,659 --> 00:04:53,180
Doris's boss,
Big Dave Brewster,

62
00:04:53,283 --> 00:04:57,058
Was married to Ann Nirdlinger,
the department store heiress.

63
00:04:57,123 --> 00:04:59,262
Tonight they were coming over for dinner.

64
00:04:59,331 --> 00:05:01,022
As Doris said,

65
00:05:01,123 --> 00:05:03,458
We were entertaining.

66
00:05:06,371 --> 00:05:08,444
Me, I don't like
entertaining.

67
00:05:11,459 --> 00:05:13,346
- How you doin', Ed?
- Okay.

68
00:05:13,443 --> 00:05:15,167
Take your coat, Ann?

69
00:05:15,267 --> 00:05:18,563
The japs had us pinned down
on Buna for somethin' like six weeks.

70
00:05:18,820 --> 00:05:21,820
I gotta tell ya,
I thought we had it tough,
but we had supply.

71
00:05:21,923 --> 00:05:26,113
The japs were eatin' bugs
and grubs and thistles.

72
00:05:26,211 --> 00:05:28,928
Anyway, one day
we bust off the beach...

73
00:05:29,027 --> 00:05:32,889
And we find Arney Bragg,
this kid missin' on recon.

74
00:05:32,995 --> 00:05:35,613
the japs had eaten the son of a bitch.

75
00:05:35,715 --> 00:05:37,657
If you'll pardon the, uh...

76
00:05:37,764 --> 00:05:41,375
Anyway, he was a scrawny, pimply kid,
nothin' to write home about.

77
00:05:41,475 --> 00:05:43,362
I mean, I never woulda,
you know.

78
00:05:45,827 --> 00:05:48,096
So, what do I say, honey?

79
00:05:48,163 --> 00:05:50,880
What do I say
when I don't like dinner?

80
00:05:50,979 --> 00:05:52,408
Come on.
what do I say?

81
00:05:52,516 --> 00:05:54,905
I say,
"Arney Bragg, again?"

82
00:05:59,651 --> 00:06:01,506
Arney Bragg, again?

83
00:06:07,587 --> 00:06:10,304
- Were you in the service, Ed?
- No, Dave, I wasn't.

84
00:06:10,404 --> 00:06:13,699
Ed was 4-f on account
of his fallen arches.

85
00:06:18,403 --> 00:06:19,613
That's tough.

86
00:06:19,683 --> 00:06:21,538
That's... That's tough.

87
00:06:26,531 --> 00:06:30,939
Yeah, I guess Doris liked
all that he-man stuff.

88
00:06:31,043 --> 00:06:33,214
Sometimes I had the feeling that

89
00:06:33,315 --> 00:06:36,097
She and Big Dave were a lot closer
than they let on.

90
00:06:36,163 --> 00:06:38,684
The signs were all there,
plain enough.

91
00:06:48,387 --> 00:06:51,257
Not that I was gonna
prance about it, mind you.

92
00:06:51,363 --> 00:06:53,152
It's a free country.

93
00:06:54,820 --> 00:06:56,161
Holdin' down the porch area, Ed?

94
00:06:57,507 --> 00:07:00,190
- That's some wife you got there.
- Yeah.

95
00:07:01,123 --> 00:07:02,978
She's a rare one.

96
00:07:05,155 --> 00:07:06,716
So, how's business,
Dave?

97
00:07:07,011 --> 00:07:09,694
Oh, uh, couldn't be better.

98
00:07:09,795 --> 00:07:12,610
These are boom times
in retailin', Ed.

99
00:07:12,675 --> 00:07:15,009
We're openin' another store
over there on carson,

100
00:07:15,107 --> 00:07:18,173
Big Dave's annex.
Now, this is strictly haberdashery.

101
00:07:18,275 --> 00:07:21,275
It's casual wear, pajamas,
ladies' undergarments and foundations,

102
00:07:21,379 --> 00:07:23,070
That type of thing.

103
00:07:24,963 --> 00:07:28,858
As a matter of fact,
I'm thinkin' of makin' Doris the comptroller.

104
00:07:32,835 --> 00:07:35,137
Listen, when the annex opens up,
you gotta stop by.

105
00:07:35,203 --> 00:07:37,178
Maybe we can update your suit
a little bit, huh?

106
00:07:41,603 --> 00:07:43,992
Course, you're in
the smock all day.

107
00:07:46,019 --> 00:07:48,091
Where do you get those things,
anyway?

108
00:07:48,163 --> 00:07:51,512
Specialty store
down in Sacramento.

109
00:08:02,307 --> 00:08:03,714
You tie your own flies.

110
00:08:03,971 --> 00:08:07,288
I mean, if you're really serious,
you tie your own flies.

111
00:08:07,395 --> 00:08:08,769
You do, uh...

112
00:08:08,867 --> 00:08:11,071
I know. It's meticulous.
I know.

113
00:08:11,171 --> 00:08:13,691
People say, hey, you can
buy flies at the store.

114
00:08:13,763 --> 00:08:16,796
The point is, there's a certain art
to the process.

115
00:08:16,899 --> 00:08:19,266
The point is not merely to provide.

116
00:08:19,363 --> 00:08:23,585
Let me point out, these fish are not
as dumb as you might think.

117
00:08:23,683 --> 00:08:25,625
Sure.
Go to the store.

118
00:08:25,731 --> 00:08:28,993
Describe to the man
where you will be fishing and for what,

119
00:08:29,091 --> 00:08:33,826
And then you might as well have the man
sell you the goddamned fish, Ed.

120
00:08:33,923 --> 00:08:35,035
My point is,

121
00:08:35,139 --> 00:08:38,041
This is a man who knows nothing,
no matter how much you tell him.

122
00:08:38,147 --> 00:08:40,830
- So sell him the goddamned fish, Ed.
- Yeah.

123
00:08:42,339 --> 00:08:43,322
Okay.

124
00:08:44,323 --> 00:08:46,210
Who gets the privilege?

125
00:08:46,307 --> 00:08:48,063
We're just closing, friend.

126
00:08:48,291 --> 00:08:49,982
Oh, happy days.

127
00:08:50,563 --> 00:08:53,825
I wish I was doing well enough
to turn away business.

128
00:08:53,923 --> 00:08:57,785
What's the problem, friend?
this is a business establishment with posted hours.

129
00:08:57,923 --> 00:08:59,516
More power to ya, brother.

130
00:08:59,619 --> 00:09:00,602
The public be damned.

131
00:09:00,771 --> 00:09:01,567
Hey...

132
00:09:01,667 --> 00:09:03,456
I'll take care of him.
you go ahead, Frank.

133
00:09:03,523 --> 00:09:05,465
Have a seat, mister.

134
00:09:05,571 --> 00:09:08,353
- You sure, Eddie?
- Yeah, yeah, go ahead.

135
00:09:11,331 --> 00:09:13,371
In your ear, mister.

136
00:09:15,427 --> 00:09:18,297
Oh, those fiery
Mediterraneans.

137
00:09:19,235 --> 00:09:22,333
Uh, say, uh,
not so fast there, brother.

138
00:09:24,835 --> 00:09:25,882
Pretty good, eh?

139
00:09:25,987 --> 00:09:27,809
Fools even the experts.

140
00:09:27,907 --> 00:09:31,256
One hundred percent human hair.
Handcrafted by Jacques

141
00:09:31,363 --> 00:09:32,890
Of San Francisco.

142
00:09:32,963 --> 00:09:36,062
I'd hate to have to tell you
what I paid for it.

143
00:09:36,163 --> 00:09:38,497
Yeah, it's a nice rug.

144
00:09:38,563 --> 00:09:40,418
I'm payin' it down
on the installment plan.

145
00:09:40,483 --> 00:09:44,313
A lot of folks live
with the pate exposed.

146
00:09:44,419 --> 00:09:46,753
They say the dames
think it's sexy,

147
00:09:46,851 --> 00:09:49,851
But for my money
it's just not good groomin'.

148
00:09:49,923 --> 00:09:53,567
And groomin' my friend,
is probably the most important thing in business.

149
00:09:53,667 --> 00:09:56,001
After personality, of course.

150
00:09:56,963 --> 00:09:59,330
Creighton Tolliver.
Pleased to know ya.

151
00:10:00,387 --> 00:10:01,729
Ed Crane.

152
00:10:02,691 --> 00:10:04,992
So, what brings you
to Santa Rosa?

153
00:10:05,091 --> 00:10:08,157
A goose, my friend.
I was chasin' a wild goose.

154
00:10:09,827 --> 00:10:11,714
Ed, have you ever heard
of venture capital?

155
00:10:11,811 --> 00:10:14,178
Risk money.
very speculative.

156
00:10:14,243 --> 00:10:18,499
Except that in certain situations
it's not, see.

157
00:10:18,563 --> 00:10:20,603
I thought I had
a prospect here

158
00:10:20,707 --> 00:10:25,148
Well, I make the haul up...
And this lousy so-and-so tells me...

159
00:10:25,251 --> 00:10:27,040
That the situation has changed.

160
00:10:27,139 --> 00:10:30,488
All of his capital's tied up
in expansion plans of his own.

161
00:10:30,595 --> 00:10:33,213
Thank you mother.
Pop goes another bubble.

162
00:10:33,315 --> 00:10:36,064
It's only the biggest business opportunity
since Henry Ford,

163
00:10:36,163 --> 00:10:38,814
And I can't seem
to interest a soul.

164
00:10:38,883 --> 00:10:39,898
Is that right?

165
00:10:40,003 --> 00:10:41,913
It's called dry cleaning.

166
00:10:43,363 --> 00:10:45,883
You heard me right, brother.
dry cleaning.

167
00:10:45,987 --> 00:10:48,670
Wash without water.

168
00:10:48,771 --> 00:10:52,251
No suds. No tumple.
No stress on the clothes.

169
00:10:52,355 --> 00:10:55,005
It's all done
with chemicals, friend.

170
00:10:55,074 --> 00:10:56,765
And here's the capper...

171
00:10:56,867 --> 00:10:58,143
No shrinkage.

172
00:10:59,043 --> 00:11:00,766
That's right.

173
00:11:00,834 --> 00:11:02,045
Dry cleaning.

174
00:11:02,115 --> 00:11:05,148
All I need is $10,000
to open up the first store.

175
00:11:05,411 --> 00:11:09,819
Then I use its cash flow
to finance another, and so on,

176
00:11:09,923 --> 00:11:13,120
Leapfrog, bootstrap myself
to a whole chain.

177
00:11:14,083 --> 00:11:15,544
Well, me and a partner.

178
00:11:17,123 --> 00:11:19,359
Cleanliness, friend.

179
00:11:19,459 --> 00:11:21,401
There's money in it.
there's a future.

180
00:11:21,507 --> 00:11:23,132
There's room to grow.

181
00:11:23,203 --> 00:11:26,269
Say, that looks pretty good.

182
00:11:26,531 --> 00:11:28,603
Let's see it
with the hairpiece on.

183
00:11:40,323 --> 00:11:42,079
Dry cleaning.

184
00:11:43,555 --> 00:11:46,817
Was I crazy
to be thinking about it?

185
00:11:46,914 --> 00:11:51,192
Was he a huckster or an opportunity,
the real Mccoy?

186
00:11:54,467 --> 00:11:58,591
My first instinct was
no, no, the whole idea was nuts.

187
00:11:58,690 --> 00:12:02,302
But maybe that was the instinct
that kept me locked in the barber shop,

188
00:12:02,403 --> 00:12:06,080
Nose against the exit
afraid to try turning the knob.

189
00:12:06,978 --> 00:12:08,255
- Honey?
- Hmm?

190
00:12:09,699 --> 00:12:11,707
Shave my legs, will ya?

191
00:12:16,803 --> 00:12:18,908
What if I could
get the money?

192
00:12:49,379 --> 00:12:51,484
It was clean.

193
00:12:52,131 --> 00:12:53,887
No water.

194
00:12:55,074 --> 00:12:56,765
Chemicals.

195
00:13:00,771 --> 00:13:02,560
Gimme a drag.

196
00:13:14,530 --> 00:13:16,156
Love ya, honey.

197
00:13:20,163 --> 00:13:21,723
What you...
uh, come in.

198
00:13:22,883 --> 00:13:25,850
Okay, yeah.
I'll see you tomorrow.

199
00:13:27,874 --> 00:13:29,565
Oh. I thought
you were the porter.

200
00:13:29,667 --> 00:13:31,576
Can I help ya?

201
00:13:31,683 --> 00:13:33,374
I'm Ed.

202
00:13:33,474 --> 00:13:35,384
Ed Crane.

203
00:13:37,570 --> 00:13:39,578
Um, I cut your hair today.

204
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:42,332
I'm the barber.

205
00:13:42,435 --> 00:13:44,922
Jesus, yeah.
The barber.

206
00:13:45,027 --> 00:13:47,678
I didn't recognize you
without the smock.

207
00:13:47,778 --> 00:13:49,720
Did I leave somethin'
at the shop?

208
00:13:49,827 --> 00:13:52,129
No. No,
it's nothing like that.

209
00:13:52,226 --> 00:13:55,455
Um, l-I might be interested
in that business proposition.

210
00:13:58,499 --> 00:13:59,644
You got the dough?

211
00:13:59,715 --> 00:14:02,136
Well, I can get it.

212
00:14:02,243 --> 00:14:04,544
Come in. Come in!

213
00:14:04,643 --> 00:14:06,017
Sit down over there.

214
00:14:06,114 --> 00:14:08,383
- Coffee?
- No.

215
00:14:08,483 --> 00:14:11,614
Well, sit down,
make yourself comfortable.

216
00:14:13,315 --> 00:14:15,420
So tell me...

217
00:14:15,651 --> 00:14:20,026
Other than putting up the money, uh,
exactly what would you want the partner to, uh...

218
00:14:20,291 --> 00:14:21,720
Do?

219
00:14:21,795 --> 00:14:23,321
Hell, nothin'.

220
00:14:23,427 --> 00:14:27,518
You're gonna want to keep
tabs on your investment,
The running of the business,

221
00:14:27,586 --> 00:14:30,139
but I'm looking for a silent partner.

222
00:14:30,243 --> 00:14:33,177
I've done the research,
I've contacted the vendors.

223
00:14:33,283 --> 00:14:34,810
The deal is set.

224
00:14:34,914 --> 00:14:38,973
Disappear, if you'd like.
Check in whenever you want.

225
00:14:39,075 --> 00:14:42,424
I want the dough.
I don't take attendance.

226
00:14:42,531 --> 00:14:43,960
And how do we share the...

227
00:14:44,066 --> 00:14:46,238
Fifty-fifty,
straight down the line.

228
00:14:46,338 --> 00:14:48,443
You and me.
Finance and expertise.

229
00:14:49,443 --> 00:14:51,330
So you got the dough then,
do ya?

230
00:14:51,427 --> 00:14:53,434
I can have it in a week.

231
00:14:53,539 --> 00:14:55,546
The barber...

232
00:14:56,994 --> 00:15:00,311
Well, I thought this trip
was gonna be a bust.

233
00:15:00,579 --> 00:15:03,481
Just shows to go ya,
when one door slams shut,

234
00:15:03,555 --> 00:15:05,410
Another one opens.

235
00:15:05,475 --> 00:15:07,711
Here's to you, uh...

236
00:15:36,227 --> 00:15:37,753
Was that a pass?

237
00:15:39,011 --> 00:15:40,385
Maybe.

238
00:15:41,347 --> 00:15:43,038
Well, you're out of line, mister

239
00:15:44,867 --> 00:15:46,328
Not a problem.

240
00:15:46,435 --> 00:15:48,093
Way out of line.

241
00:15:48,194 --> 00:15:50,104
Right.

242
00:15:50,210 --> 00:15:51,934
Strictly business.

243
00:15:54,498 --> 00:15:55,840
Okay.

244
00:16:06,307 --> 00:16:08,958
I sent it to Dave
the next morning.

245
00:16:09,058 --> 00:16:10,717
Then I waited.

246
00:16:30,434 --> 00:16:32,704
- Frank?
- Huh?

247
00:16:35,426 --> 00:16:37,215
This hair.

248
00:16:38,179 --> 00:16:39,935
Yeah?

249
00:16:40,034 --> 00:16:41,758
You ever wonder about it?

